// Classify each change:
// 1. Add field with default:
// 2. Rename field:
// 3. Remove field with default:
// 4. Change type:
// 5. Add nullable field:

exercises.expected_solution:
// 1. Add field with default: BACKWARD COMPATIBLE
//    Old consumers see 'UNKNOWN' for new events. No data loss.
//    Old producers don't set it — new consumers see default 'UNKNOWN'. Safe.

// 2. Rename field 'price' to 'unitPrice': BREAKING
//    Old consumers look for 'price' — not found. Get null/error.
//    Old events don't have 'unitPrice' — new consumers get null/error.
//    Schema Registry rejects this.

// 3. Remove field 'notes' (has default null): FORWARD COMPATIBLE
//    New producers don't send 'notes'. Old consumers see null (default).
//    But: old producers send 'notes', new schema ignores it.
//    Backward compat depends on whether old data needs 'notes'.
//    With BACKWARD compatibility: BREAKING (old data has 'notes', new schema can't read it)
//    With FORWARD compatibility: OK

// 4. Change 'qty' type int → string: BREAKING
//    Old data has binary int. New schema expects string encoding. Can't read.
//    Schema Registry rejects this.

// 5. Add nullable field with null default: BACKWARD COMPATIBLE
//    ['null','string'] union with default null.
//    Old consumers: new events have the field as null. Safe.
//    Old producers: field absent → new consumers see null (default). Safe.

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("1: Backward Compatible (has default)");
        System.out.println("2: BREAKING (rename)");
        System.out.println("3: Forward Compatible (removal with default)");
        System.out.println("4: BREAKING (type change)");
        System.out.println("5: Backward Compatible (nullable with default)");
    }
}

